03655nam a22005535i 9780520937949DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20042004cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209379497 a10.1525/97805209379492doi  a(DE-B1597)521153  a(OCoLC)1110714412  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a959.6042222/eng1 aHinton, Alexander Laban, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy Did They Kill? :bCambodia in the Shadow of Genocide /cAlexander Laban Hinton. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (382 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Series in Public Anthropology ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tTimeline -- tPersonages -- tForeword -- tIntroduction: In the Shadow of Genocide -- tPart ONE. The Prison without Walls -- tPart TWO. The Fire without Smoke -- tNote on Transliteration -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOf all the horrors human beings perpetrate, genocide stands near the top of the list. Its toll is staggering: well over 100 million dead worldwide. Why Did They Kill? is one of the first anthropological attempts to analyze the origins of genocide. In it, Alexander Hinton focuses on the devastation that took place in Cambodia from April 1975 to January 1979 under the Khmer Rouge in order to explore why mass murder happens and what motivates perpetrators to kill. Basing his analysis on years of investigative work in Cambodia, Hinton finds parallels between the Khmer Rouge and the Nazi regimes. Policies in Cambodia resulted in the deaths of over 1.7 million of that country's 8 million inhabitants-almost a quarter of the population--who perished from starvation, overwork, illness, malnutrition, and execution. Hinton considers this violence in light of a number of dynamics, including the ways in which difference is manufactured, how identity and meaning are constructed, and how emotionally resonant forms of cultural knowledge are incorporated into genocidal ideologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aGenocidexCambodia. 0aGenocidezCambodia. 0aPolitical atrocitiesxCambodia. 0aPolitical atrocitieszCambodia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520937949423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520937949.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles